Atttention to the reader 

Since 2016, she’s been my forever travel companion, my anchor, my everything💕💫. There’s no replacing her, and seeing her smile amidst these breathtaking views makes my heart full.

This trip to this winter wonderland was one we’d dreamed of for so long, and we couldn’t have chosen a better way to kickstart #2025 than with the snowy magic of Gulmarg.

With temperatures dipping below freezing, we kept our outfits simple yet cozy, embracing the chill and the beauty around us. Every moment here, from the snowflakes kissing our cheeks to the laughter we shared, was a reminder of how precious these adventures are when shared with the one who means the world. Here’s to love, warmth, and many more journeys together and Shoutout to @crowdedcanyon for capturing these amazing shots❤️‍🔥💯

These were the questions asked in my interview, based on my  last reel about star air 
1. Why did you not complete your 12th standard?
Answer-Due to personal reasons, I couldn’t complete it at that time, but I’ve focused on gaining practical skills and experience since then.

2. Do you plan to complete it in the future?
Answer-Yes, I plan to complete it through open or distance learning soon.

3. How serious are you about building a career in aviation?
Answer-Very serious. I’ve prepared myself through training, grooming, and industry knowledge. This is my long-term goal.

4. What skills do you have that make you suitable for this role?
Answer-I have strong communication skills, a calm attitude, a professional appearance, and I work well under pressure and in teams.

5. How will you handle the challenges of cabin crew life without a full education background?
Answer-I believe practical skills, strong work ethic, and adaptability matter most. I’m quick to learn, emotionally strong, and fully prepared for the demands of this role.

Yes, 12th standard is important for most airlines… but if you’ve not completed it, don’t give up just yet!
Some airlines still give you a chance by asking a few key questions during the interview. Here’s what they might ask 👇
1.Why did you not complete your 12th standard?
2.Do you plan to complete it in the future?
3.How serious are you about building a career in aviation?
4.What skills do you have that make you suitable for this role?
5.How will you handle the challenges of cabin crew life without a full education background?

✨ Tip: Be honest, confident, and show your passion for the job. Many have made it — so can you

#cabincrew #cabincrewinterviewpreparation #cabincrewinformation #featured #cabinlifestyle #interviewquestions

They may look like simple questions, but trust me, they matter 👀

These popped up randomly while scanning at the interview venue — and every answer says something about you💓

🎥 Questions like:
– How did you find out about the interview?
– Who inspires you?
– Why Star Air?
– How’s the venue?
– Your location & age?
– Your favorite occasion?

📌Don’t brush these off — answer them smartly & honestly. These are your first impressions!

🎤 Part II is coming next – stay tuned
#starair #cabincrewinterviewpreparation #cabincrewinformation #cabincrewinterview #cabincrewinterview #cabincrewinterviewquestion #feature

1)Why do you want to join IndiGo?
Answer:IndiGo is India’s leading airline known for punctuality and service. I admire its professional work culture and growth opportunities, and I’d be proud to represent a brand that values safety, efficiency, and customer satisfaction.

3)What is the role of a cabin crew?
Answer:A cabin crew ensures the safety, security, and comfort of passengers during a flight. They also handle emergencies, serve meals, and create a pleasant flying experience.

4)How will you handle a rude passenger?
Answer:I would stay calm, listen patiently, and respond politely. My aim would be to resolve the issue while maintaining professionalism and ensuring the safety and comfort of everyone on board.

5.Are you willing to relocate?
Answer:Yes, I am open to relocation. I understand that it’s part of the job and I’m excited for the experience and opportunities it brings.

6. What is your strength and weakness?
Answer:Strength: I’m a good communicator and stay calm under pressure.
Weakness: I used to overthink, but now I focus on staying present and taking practical steps.

7)What would you do if a co-worker is not cooperating during a flight?
Answer:I’d try to communicate respectfully and resolve it professionally. If it affects safety or service, I’d inform the senior crew or take guidance from the in-charge.

Wish there was no Group Discussion round, right? 😅 Just imagine if airlines stopped taking GDs altogether

How  peaceful life would be🌸🤭
But let’s be real — that’s never going to happen.
Because GDs are the biggest clue for recruiters to judge how well you communicate, think on your feet, and handle pressure.

So tell me honestly in the comments —
👉 Are you scared of the GD round?
Don’t hold back, give me your genuine answer

✨ From my side:
✅ It’s okay to be nervous — most people are🗒️
✅ Practice doesn’t make you perfect, but it makes you better and more confident.
✅ Focus more on listening than just speaking.
✅ You don’t have to be the loudest, just the clearest.

I’ll be dropping some GD tips in the next few posts to help you conquer that fear — so stay tuned💝
#CabinCrewTips #GroupDiscussion #AviationInterview #CabinCrewDreams #GDPreparation #CabinCrewLife”
